knowledge_graph.title: Yogurt
knowledge_graph.description: Yogurt is a food produced by bacterial fermentation of milk. Fermentation of sugars in the milk by these bacteria produces lactic acid, which acts on milk protein to give yogurt its texture and characteristic tart flavor. Cow's milk is most commonly used to make yogurt.

related_questions.question: How healthy is yogurt for you?
related_questions.snippet: Yogurts can be high in protein, calcium, vitamins, and live culture, or probiotics, which can enhance the gut microbiota. These can offer protection for bones and teeth and help prevent digestive problems. Low-fat yogurt can be a useful source of protein on a weight-loss diet.
related_questions.title: Yogurt: Types, health benefits, and risks - MedicalNewsToday

related_questions.question: Is it spelled yogurt or yoghurt?
related_questions.snippet: In English, spelling variations include yogurt, yoghurt, and to a lesser extent yoghourt or yogourt. In the United Kingdom, Australia, New Zealand and South Africa the word is usually spelled yoghurt, while in the United States the spelling is yogurt.
related_questions.title: Yogurt - Wikipedia

related_questions.question: Can I eat yogurt everyday?
related_questions.snippet: Consuming one to two cups of low-fat Greek yogurt daily can be a healthy addition to your diet without making it difficult to maintain your weight.
related_questions.title: Health Benefits of Greek Yogurt - WebMD

related_questions.question: What is the healthiest yogurt?
related_questions.snippet: Greek yoghurt is generally considered to be highly nutritious, helped in part by its association with the heart-healthy Mediterranean diet. Traditionally it was made by straining out the liquid whey, which concentrated its protein (and therefore its overall nutrient) content.

buttons.subtitle: What Is Yogurt Made Of?
buttons.title: Yogurt - The Nutrition Source - Harvard University
buttons.snippet: Yogurt is made when heated milk is combined with bacteria, specifically Lactobacillus bulgaricus and Streptococcus thermophilus, and left to sit for several hours at a warm temperature (110-115°F). Additional types of lactobacilli and bifidobacteria may be added.
